K₃ is the ONLY complete graph that is K₃-poisoned!
(Because I(K₃,-1/3) = 1+3(-1/3) = 0, but I(K_n,-1/3) = 1-n/3 ≠ 0 for n≠3)

======================================================================
CORRECTION: K₃ POISON IS INCOMPLETE FOR H=21!
======================================================================

The K₃ poison (I divisible by 1+3x) captures:
  - K₃ itself (I = 1+3x)
  - P₄ and K₁⊔K₃ (I = 1+4x+3x²)

But it MISSES graphs with different α vectors:
  - K₆-2e: I = 1+6x+2x², I(-1/3) = 1-2+2/9 = -7/9 ≠ 0
  - K₈-e: I = 1+8x+x², I(-1/3) = 1-8/3+1/9 = -14/9 ≠ 0
  - K₁₀: I = 1+10x, I(-1/3) = 1-10/3 = -7/3 ≠ 0

These graphs are NOT K₃-poisoned but also have I(G,2)=21.
The full H≠21 proof requires ruling out EACH of these as Ω(T).

RESOLUTION: The n≤5 exhaustive search found only 1+4x+3x² because
the other α vectors require n≥6 vertices. The K₃ poison is a
PARTIAL explanation, covering the 4-vertex cases. The full proof
of H≠21 requires additional arguments for the large-vertex cases.

STRUCTURAL CHECK: Can K₆-2e be Ω(T)?
  K₆-2e has 6 vertices and 13 edges.
  In Ω(T): vertices = directed odd cycles, edges = vertex-sharing.
  K₆-2e means 6 odd cycles with exactly 2 disjoint pairs.
  For 3-cycles: 2 disjoint pairs need at least 2×6=12 tournament vertices.
  But the 4 non-disjoint cycles share vertices, reducing this.
  This is a complex combinatorial constraint that needs case analysis.
